Agave lecheguilla

   [2897.jpg]
    Authority   Torrey
      Family    Liliopsida:Liliidae:Asparagales:Agavaceae
     Synonyms
   Common names lecheguilla, Tula istle, dwarf agave
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 2897

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION The plant forms a rosette with no trunk above ground
   and with 25-50 leaves. By the end of its lifespand it produces a flower
   pole, 1.5-2 m high with light yellow flowers. USES A fiber is produced
   from the immature leaves and used in brushes and as a substitute for
   bristle. KILLING T It can tolerate -9Â°C without damage. GROWING PERIOD
   Perennial. It require 6 years to the first harvest, and can
   subsequently harvested twice a year for another 6 years. COMMON NAMES
   Istle, Ixtle, Mexican fiber, Lechhuguilla, Tula istle, Tampico fiber.
   FURTHER INF Istle can be found growing wild in Mexico, at altitudes
   between 180-2000 m. In southern United States, it is regarded as a weed
   and is stated to be poisonous to sheep and goats.

   Sources
   SOURCES (A. lecheguilla Torrey)
   Purseglove J 1972 pp 14 [RAIN, DRA, LIMITS, USE]
   Roecklein J 1987 pp 121 [USE]
   Duke J 1975 pp 5 [RAIN, TEMP, PH]
   Gentry H 1982 pp 652
   Kirby R 1963 pp 405-410 [PH, RAIN, DRA, USE, LIMIT]

